data.title: Gilead posts higher profit on demand for HIV drugs, but overall sales dip
data.description:
By Deena Beasley

Gilead Sciences said on Thursday its HIV drug sales rose 4% to $5.3 billion in the third quarter including $39 million for its new prevention drug Yeztugo, helping to boost its profit.

The company's overall product sales, however, fell 2% to $7.3 billion due to lower COVID-19 and cell therapy sales.

Shares of Gilead, which closed down a fraction, were down 3.5% at $114.30 in after-hours trading.

Wall Street expected sales of Yeztugo, which has an annual U.S. list price of about $28,000, at $37.5 million, according to LSEG. The drug is a twice-yearly injection approved by U.S. regulators in June to prevent HIV in adults and adolescents at high risk of contracting the deadly infection.

"We are really pleased with the progress of the Yeztugo launch," Gilead CEO Daniel O'Day said in an interview, noting that 75% of U.S. payers have agreed to cover the drug, and the company expects that to increase to 90% by mid-2026.

CVS Health , which runs the largest U.S. pharmacy benefit manager, has still not added Yeztugo to its commercial plans, due to issues including the drug's high cost.

Gilead, based in Foster City, California, reported a quarterly profit of $2.43 per share, compared with $1.00 a year earlier, when it took a large impairment charge. Total revenue rose 3% to $7.77 billion, including $400 million from a one-time sale of intellectual property.

The results beat average Wall Street estimates of $2.13 a share on revenue of $7.45 billion.

Gilead said sales in its liver disease portfolio rose 12% to $819 million, while sales of COVID treatment Veklury fell 60% to $277 million due to lower rates of COVID-related hospitalizations.

Sales of cell therapy products decreased 11% to $432 million, reflecting more competition, while sales of cancer drug Trodelvy rose 7% to $357 million.

For the full year, Gilead raised the lower end of its adjusted earnings estimate by 10 cents to $8.05 per share, but left the top end unchanged at $8.25.

The company also bumped up the low end of its expectations for 2025 product sales to $28.4 billion from $28.3 billion, while the upper end of the range was unchanged at $28.7 billion.

data.title: Quaker Houghton Announces Third Quarter 2025 Results
data.description:
Quaker Houghton, a global leader in industrial process fluids, has released its financial results for the third quarter of 2025. The company reported a solid performance despite challenging market conditions, driven by new business wins and strategic initiatives.

Financial Highlights

For the third quarter of 2025, Quaker Houghton reported net sales of $493.8 million, marking a 7% increase year-over-year. Organic sales volumes grew by 3%, bolstered by new business wins contributing approximately 5%. The company achieved a net income of $30.5 million, translating to earnings per diluted share (EPS) of $1.75. On a non-GAAP basis, net income was $36.3 million, with non-GAAP EPS of $2.08, reflecting a 10% increase year-over-year. Adjusted EBITDA stood at $82.9 million, a 5% rise from the previous year, with adjusted EBITDA margins at 16.8%.

Business and Operational Highlights

Quaker Houghton experienced growth across all segments, with the Asia/Pacific region leading with an 8% increase in organic sales volumes. The Americas and EMEA segments also saw improvements, although the Americas faced softer end market conditions. The company's strategic focus on new business wins and maintaining consistent operating margins contributed to its robust performance.

Strategic Initiatives and Corporate Developments

During the third quarter, Quaker Houghton generated $51.4 million in operating cash flow and reduced its net leverage ratio to 2.4x. The company also repurchased 29,791 shares for $3.8 million. These actions reflect the company's commitment to strengthening its balance sheet and returning value to shareholders.

Management's Perspective

Joe Berquist, Chief Executive Officer and President, commented, "Third quarter results were strong, resulting from the team’s disciplined execution of our strategy. We achieved a 7% increase in sales on 3% organic volume growth, and a 5% improvement in adjusted EBITDA in the quarter, despite a softer than anticipated end market environment. Our performance was driven by new business wins of approximately 5% globally and amplified by continued momentum in Asia/Pacific."

Future Outlook

Looking ahead, Quaker Houghton anticipates that the current soft market environment will persist through the end of the year, with normal seasonality expected. The company remains confident in its ability to convert its sales pipeline and execute ongoing cost and productivity initiatives. Management expects to deliver year-over-year revenue and earnings growth in the fourth quarter and is building momentum for sustained above-market growth in 2026 and beyond.

Original SEC Filing: QUAKER CHEMICAL CORP [ KWR ] - 8-K - Oct. 30, 2025

data.title: Ingersoll Rand Reports Third Quarter 2025 Results
data.description:
Ingersoll Rand Inc., a global provider of mission-critical flow creation and life science and industrial solutions, has released its financial results for the third quarter of 2025. The company reported strong performance driven by its competitive differentiator, Ingersoll Rand Execution Excellence (IRX).

Financial Highlights

For the third quarter of 2025, Ingersoll Rand reported:

  • Orders of $1.942 billion, up 8% from the third quarter of 2024.
  • Revenues of $1.955 billion, up 5% from the same period last year.
  • Net income attributable to Ingersoll Rand Inc. of $244 million, or $0.61 per share.
  • Adjusted net income of $346 million, or $0.86 per share.
  • Adjusted EBITDA of $545 million, up 2%, with a margin of 27.9%.
  • Operating cash flow of $355 million and free cash flow of $326 million.
  • Liquidity of $3.8 billion as of September 30, 2025, including $1.2 billion of cash on hand and undrawn capacity of $2.6 billion under available credit facilities.

Business and Operational Highlights

The company operates in two main segments:

  • Industrial Technologies and Services Segment (IT&S): This segment saw orders of $1.522 billion, up 7%, and revenues of $1.541 billion, up 5%. However, organic revenues were down 2%. The segment's adjusted EBITDA was $448 million, down 1%, with a margin of 29.0%.
  • Precision and Science Technologies Segment (P&ST): This segment reported orders of $420 million, up 11%, and revenues of $415 million, up 5%. Organic revenues were up 2%. The segment's adjusted EBITDA was $128 million, up 8%, with a margin of 30.8%.

Strategic Initiatives and Corporate Developments

Ingersoll Rand remains in a strong financial position with liquidity of $3.8 billion. The company generated $355 million of cash flow from operating activities and invested $29 million in capital expenditures, resulting in free cash flow of $326 million. The company also deployed $249 million to mergers and acquisitions, including the acquisition of Dave Barry Plastics, a leading manufacturer of custom clean room solutions, in August. Additionally, Ingersoll Rand returned $201 million to shareholders through share repurchases and dividend payments.

Management's Perspective

Vicente Reynal, chairman and chief executive officer of Ingersoll Rand, commented, "We delivered positive organic orders growth in the third quarter across both segments. Our performance demonstrates the resilience of our business, which combined with our strong balance sheet, enables durable long-term growth. We remain well positioned for future growth with our proven agile business model, operational excellence, and ownership mindset."

Future Outlook

Ingersoll Rand has adjusted its guidance for full-year 2025. The company now expects:

  • Total revenue growth of 4-6%.
  • Organic revenue growth of (2)-0%.
  • Adjusted EBITDA of $2.060 billion to $2.090 billion, representing a 2-4% year-over-year increase.
  • Adjusted EPS of $3.25 to $3.31, representing a (1%) to 1% year-over-year change.

Original SEC Filing: Ingersoll Rand Inc. [ IR ] - 8-K - Oct. 30, 2025

data.title: Top News Today/Canada: Spin Master's Toy Revenue Hit By Trade Tensions
data.description:
HEADLINES

Spin Master Quarterly Earnings Fall as Toy Revenue is Hit By Trade Uncertainty

Children's entertainment company Spin Master was squeezed in the latest quarter by a drop in toy sales as market uncertainties brought on by tariff policies weighed.

Shares settled 9.8% higher at C$21.22.

The Canadian parent of brands including PAW Patrol, Melissa & Doug and Rubik's Cube, logged a drop in net income to $106.8 million, or $1.03 a share, from $140.1 million, or $1.32, a year earlier.

Earnings before interest, taxes, depreciation and amortization on an underlying basis fell to $195.5 million from $277.5 million, but came in ahead of the $182.1 consensus forecast of analysts polled by FactSet. Revenue for the three months fell 17% to $734.7 million.

Restaurant Brands Shrugs Off Consumer Caution with Strong Quarterly Sales

Restaurant Brands International is proving resilient against a cautious consumer, posting higher quarterly sales driven by its Tim Hortons chain and a pickup from Burger King's international operations.

Shares rose 1.9% to C$93.89.

The quick-service restaurant company reported a 7% rise in revenue of $2.45 billion, topping Wall Street expectations of $2.39 billion.

Leading the charge were the company's Tim Hortons and international businesses, which together represent over two-thirds of the company's adjusted operating income. They posted comparable sales growth of 4.2% and 6.5%, respectively. Burger King comparative sales rose 3.1%.

Pricing Discipline Helps Restaurant Brands Stay Afloat Burger King's Beef Prices Are Still Elevated

Canada Anticipates G7 Critical Mineral Deals to Counter China Dominance

Group of Seven energy officials are set to unveil government-backed deals as early as Friday that mark a unified effort to accelerate production of critical minerals to counter China's dominance, says Canadian Energy and Resources Minister Tim Hodgson.

Canada is hosting this week a G7 meeting in Toronto of energy and environment officials. The gathering concludes Friday, and Hodgson said in an interview the group will produce tangible results.

"We want words turned into action," said Hodgson, a former senior executive at Goldman Sachs. He said there will be "real deals, real examples of virtually all of the G7 members, plus some of our allies, stepping up with real contracts to make critical mineral opportunities into critical mineral production."

Bausch Health Shares Climb on Third-Quarter Profit, Revenue Rise

Bausch Health shares jumped after reporting a profit in the third quarter as its gastroenterology and medical devices segments supported strong revenue growth.

Shares settled at C$9.25, 12.5% higher.

The Canadian pharmaceutical and medical device company reported late Wednesday a 7% rise in revenue to $2.68 billion. The company's Salix segment, which specializes in gastroenterology, saw a 12% rise in revenue to $716 million, and a 25% rise for Solita, the Bausch's medical devices company which focuses on aesthetic treatments like skin tightening and body contouring.

Onex Shares Rise on Deal With AIG to Buy Specialty Insurer Convex for $7 Billion

Onex's shares were up after the private-equity firm teamed with American International Group to buy privately-held property and casualty insurer Convex for $7 billion.

Shares rose 3.5% to C$122.45.

AIG, which will end up with minority stakes in both Convex and Onex and is committing capital to Onex's private equity and credit strategies, saw its shares rise 1.1% to $78.84.

Onex and AIG said they have agreed to jointly acquire the entire interest held by Onex Partners V and its co-investors in Convex.

Algoma Steel Shares Slide After Tariffs Drag Quarterly Results, CEO Plans to Retire

Algoma Steel Group shares fell after tariffs dented third-quarter results, signaling persistent financial headwinds, and it said its chief executive will step down.

Shares settled down 6.4% at C$5.59.

The embattled Canadian steelmaker late Wednesday said the impact of tariffs on Canadian sales were C$32 million, and that direct tariff expense came to C$89.7 million, whereas last year there was no such sales impact or expense.

Corus Entertainment's Fourth-Quarter Loss Widens as Revenue Declines

Corus Entertainment's fiscal fourth-quarter loss widened as fewer ad dollars coming in continues to drag on revenue.

The embattled Canadian media company posted a widened net loss of C$277.1 million, or C$1.39 a share for the three months ended Aug. 31, compared with a loss of C$25.7 million, or C$0.13 a share, in the comparable quarter a year ago.

Adjusted loss, which excludes one-off costs and exceptional items came to C$0.36 a share. According to FactSet, analysts were expecting a loss of C$0.10 a share.

Revenue fell to C$232.1 million from C$269.4 million, lower than the C$236.2 million analysts anticipated for the period.

AltaGas Swings to Quarterly Loss, Affirms Full-Year Earnings Guidance

AltaGas swung to a loss in the third quarter despite benefiting from stronger global export volumes, though the Canadian energy-infrastructure company stuck with its target for underlying earnings for the year.

AltaGas recorded a loss of C$25 million, or C$0.08 a share, against net income a year earlier of C$9 million, or C$0.03.

Earnings before interest, taxes, depreciation and amortization on a so-called normalized basis that strips out items that can vary substantially came in at C$268 million, down from C$294 million in the same quarter last year but just ahead of the C$265 million mean estimate of analysts polled by FactSet.

TALKING POINT

The Canada-U.S. Trade War Is Pushing Carney Closer to Xi

By Vipal Monga, James T. Areddy and Yoko Kubota

Canadian Prime Minister Mark Carney spent much of his first six months in office trying to persuade the U.S. to lower tariffs on Canadian goods. With hopes for a speedy resolution now dashed, Carney is turning to America's biggest rival, China.

Carney is expected to meet with Chinese leader Xi Jinping on Friday at the APEC leaders summit in South Korea. It will be the first official meeting between the two countries' leaders since 2017, when Justin Trudeau was Canada's prime minister, and marks a significant thaw in a relationship that has been mired in acrimony for several years.

Repairing relations with China has become a priority for Carney, who is seeking other markets to offset the damage caused by U.S. tariffs on Canadian exports like steel, aluminum and lumber. Canada is trying to reopen the Chinese market to agricultural products like canola oil, pork and seafood, on which China has imposed tariffs in retaliation for Canadian duties on its electric vehicles.

"This is our second-largest trading partner. This is the second-largest economy in the world," said Carney on Monday, explaining why he thinks Canada needs a pragmatic approach to engagement with China. "This is one of the most influential actors in terms of the global system such as it is, and it is a country with whom we had no senior-level contact for seven years."

The price of better relations with China may not be cheap. To get tariffs on agricultural exports lifted, China has demanded that Canada lower a 100% tariff on Chinese electric vehicles. That would put Canada in the position of having to choose farmers over its auto industry, which would suffer if cheap Chinese vehicles came into the market.

"Give it to the Chinese, they are pretty good at weaponizing some of these relationships," said Jacob Funk Kirkegaard, senior fellow at Bruegel, a Brussels think tank.

While the leaders of Canada's canola-producing provinces have supported the EV-for-canola tariff, Carney has so far been noncommittal. He cautioned that a deal with China on electric cars could hurt its dealings with the U.S. "It's not that simple," he said, earlier this month. "Nor is the relationship in the auto sector that simple as just open the door to China here with no impact on the relationship with the United States."

Canada has had little official contact with China since 2018, when Canada detained Huawei Technologies executive Meng Wanzhou on a U.S. request. China then arrested two Canadians, and it took a complex swap in 2021 to break the stalemate. Relations never fully recovered.

Canada has since accused China of interfering in its elections, restricted Chinese investments in infrastructure and mining projects and accused the country of acting as an "increasingly disruptive global power" in a report on Canada's Indo-Pacific strategy.

China has appeared to seize on President Trump's arrival in the White House-and his tariffs and calls to turn Canada into the 51st state-as an opening to mend fences with Ottawa. Beijing responded positively to Justin Trudeau's exit as prime minister in March. In June, Carney spoke by telephone with Chinese Premier Li Qiang, and the two met in New York in September.

In recent months, Canada has begun exporting natural gas to China and referring to it as a "strategic partner." Beijing has said there is "positive momentum" between the two countries.

"They are facing the same pressure, the same sanctions, the same tactics and restrictions imposed by the U.S. unilaterally," Wang Huiyao, president of Beijing-based think tank Center for China and Globalization, said of China and Canada. "I'm sure they have a lot of common feelings."

Canada's warming relationship with China stands in contrast to its rocky ride with the U.S. Canada has been trying to persuade the U.S. to lower 50% tariffs on steel and aluminum, but talks between the countries were scuttled last week after Trump became angry at an anti-tariff television commercial sponsored by the Canadian province of Ontario. The U.S. ambassador to Canada, Pete Hoekstra, on Monday said in a local television interview that "Canada burned the bridges with America." In Asia this week for meetings with regional leaders, Trump also closed the door to further talks with Carney. "I'm not going to be meeting with him for a while," he said to reporters on Air Force One.

Chinese officials have been more positive. Earlier this month, China's ambassador to Canada, Wang Di, sent overtures to Canada. "China has always regarded Canada as a friend and partner, and is willing to move forward with Canada," he wrote in an opinion piece in the Ottawa-based publication the Hill Times.

Some former Canadian officials cautioned that Carney could find dealing with China as challenging as dealing with the U.S., despite the recent softening in tone.

"My one big warning is, tread carefully when dealing with China," said Brian Clow, former deputy chief of staff for Trudeau. China can be as ruthless in negotiations as the Trump administration, he said, noting that Beijing also uses tariffs to punish other countries.

Shi Yinhong, a distinguished professor at Renmin University of China, said the Carney-Xi meeting is unlikely to result in major breakthroughs, though the two leaders could agree on smaller points. Canada would have limitations on the scope of any trade deal, Shi said. "Canadians will say that, even if Trump is not good, I will not agree with China's positions," he said.

Also complicating things for Carney is Trump. The U.S. insisted that the U.S., Mexico, Canada free-trade agreement that was negotiated during Trump's first term include a clause that effectively barred any of the countries from signing agreements with "nonmarket economies," a description aimed specifically at China, said Clow.

"If the Canadian government thinks it's going to all of a sudden do a big deal with China, it should think again," Clow said. "The Americans won't let them."

SATS ASA: Initiation of share buyback program
data.description:
The Board of Directors of SATS ASA ("SATS" or "the Company") has resolved to initiate a share buyback program to be executed in accordance with the authorization granted to the Board of Directors by the Annual General Meeting of SATS held on 28 April 2025 ("the 2025 AGM").

The share buyback program will commence on 31 October 2025 and end no later than the Company's Annual General Meeting of 2026. The buyback program authorizes the repurchase of shares for a total consideration of up to NOK 100 million, and a maximum of 3,500,000 shares. SATS' holding of own shares may, however, not at any point exceed the authorization granted by the 2025 AGM. The purpose of the program is to optimize the share capital structure through a redemption of treasury shares, which is considered to be beneficial for the Company's shareholders.

SATS has engaged DNB Carnegie, a part of DNB Bank ASA, to manage and carry out the share repurchases in the market. No acquisition will be made during a 30-day period prior to the Company's reporting of a quarterly report.

The share buyback program will be carried out in accordance with Regulation (EU) No 596/2014 (the "Market Abuse Regulation") and Commission Delegated Regulation (EU) No 2016/1052 (the "Safe Harbour Regulation").

The Company reserves the right to make subsequent changes to the above terms for the program and will in such case make appropriate announcements in this respect.

For further information, please contact:

obliged to make public pursuant to the EU Market Abuse Regulation and subject to the disclosure requirements pursuant to Section 5-12 the Norwegian Securities Trading Act.

data.title: Netflix Announces a 10-for-1 Stock Split. The Stock Rises. — Barrons.com
data.description:
By Tae Kim

Netflix is splitting its stock.

On Thursday, the company said its board of directors authorized a 10-for-1 stock split of its shares.

"The purpose of the stock split is to reset the market price of the Company's common stock to a range that will be more accessible to employees who participate in the Company's stock option program," Netflix said in the release.

Netflix shares rose by 2.9% following the news.

The stock split will be effective at the market open on Nov. 17.

Last month, Netflix shares fell after the streaming company reported earnings below expectations, citing a continuing dispute with Brazilian tax authorities had negatively impacted financial results in the quarter.

data.title: Exxon Earnings Are Coming. Expect Questions About Growth. — Barrons.com
data.description:
By Avi Salzman

Exxon Mobil is growing its oil production at a time of falling oil prices — a decision that has historically led to problems for energy companies. The wisdom of that strategy could be tested when the company reports third quarter earnings on Friday.

So far, Exxon's moves have paid off. The oil giant has invested to expand production during good times and bad over the past few years, and investors have mostly rewarded the decision. Its oil-equivalent production — a metric that includes products like natural gas — is on track to grow to 5.4 million barrels a day by 2030, from 4.3 million in 2024. Shares are up 8% this year even though oil prices are down.

The company is expected to report $1.82 of earnings per share, down from $1.92 in the same quarter last year. Results should be hurt by low oil prices, but helped by strong refining margins.

Exxon may need to make some tough decisions if international oil prices fall into the $50 range, however. They have dropped about 14% this year to a recent $64 per barrel.

Write to Avi Salzman at avi.salzman@barrons.com

data.title: Netflix announces ten-for-one forward stock split
data.description:
Netflix on Thursday announced a ten-for-one forward stock split plan of its common stock, making the company's shares more affordable for retail investors.

Netflix's shares, which have gained more than 360% over the past three years, were up 3% at $1,123.49 in extended trading.

Each shareholder of the company will receive nine additional shares for each share held, after close of trading on Nov 10. Trading is expected to begin on a split adjusted basis at market open on November 17, the company said.
